  "reasoning_summary": "Annual macro-calibration conventions in RBC and DSGE models most frequently settle at 0.5 or 1.0. Aggregate Euler-equation evidence has historically produced very low point estimates with wide confidence regions, while microdata studies of nondurable consumption generally yield moderate positive elasticities. This combination implies a right-skewed distribution with the bulk of probability mass between 0.3 and 1.0 and a thin upper tail beyond 1.5 in standard representative-agent settings."
}

